The paper deals with a problem of information spreading in a population of agents, which involves pairwise interactions and has applications in chemical reaction networks. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) or the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. However, the paper specifically focuses on the design of a protocol that uses oscillatory dynamics to suppress false rumors and amplify confirmed rumors, which suggests that it may belong to the Dynamical Systems (cs.DS) or the Signal Processing (cs.SP) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves the analysis of the protocol's performance and complexity, which suggests that it may also belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-categories. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DS and cs.SI, followed by cs.SY, cs.GT, and cs.IT.
